{
  "text": "Generalization is performed in essence by i) inducing equivalence classes and ii) merging paths to more general and productive ones. As equivalence classes group elements whose exchange in a N L pattern causes a change in the corresponding meaning with respect to an argument slot, they are identified by searching for differences in patterns which also account for a distinction in the corresponding meaning. In particular, we explore an idea from previous work [CITATION_1] stating that sets of substitutable elements in a group of N Ls represent an equivalence class if they can account for the difference in the argument of a given slot. Given for instance the formmeaning pairings depicted on the left side of the arrow in the following example, one can easily infer the correspondences shown on the right side. (6) pinktwo kicks kick(pink2)",
  "citation_candidates": [
